 @Dempig  As you already know (as other people have pointed out as you post this stuff everywhere), the only issues with Ryzen CPU's was a motherboard manufacturer messing up, or people improperly installing their CPU.
 And  issues with VRAM, if there were any, were clearly so rare I haven't been able to find out anything about that. I have had three AMD GPU's and not had any of these problems, and a search with nothing about it shows it must not of been widespread.
 Even if it was a thing, it would be obvious you had a problem and should get a replacement GPU, the missing ROPS not so much. Many people could have this problem and not even know they weren't getting what 'value' they (over)paid for.

 @nexor7809   @nexor7809  Lol what? You serious? So if you just bought a 5070ti for 1350,- and the prices drop within 4 days and you can get a 5080 for the same price, you wouldn't do it? 
Fyi: i hadn't even opened and used the 5070ti yet, but even if I would have I wouldn't skip a beat and return to switch. Here in the netherlands we have 30 days (some stores 14) to return hardware no questions asked. If  anything looks used, so it degrades the value, your returns can be cut and you'll get a bit less back. The product will then be sold as "second chance" for a reduced price.
I don't see a problem with this system. It's fair.

@SandTiger42  To be honest, this issue is quite complicated.  

First, I am a master's student, and I primarily use my computer for research. My project requires CUDA, and choosing an AMD GPU would mean I have to make significant modifications to my code to adapt to the lack of CUDA support.  

Second, there's the pricing of AMD products in Taiwan. Perhaps due to exchange rates, their prices here are often much higher than the MSRP. Additionally, AMD GPUs have historically been in short supply or even out of stock in Taiwan. This was the case with both the 6000 and 7000 series. However, if AMD manages to resolve this issue this time, I might still consider purchasing one and setting up an additional computer with my current RTX 3080 to continue my research.

 @so-u5c  I'm a big fan of overclocking, I frequently have gotten shot down because I said my 6800xt outperforms a 3090 in most things and even in RT its extremely close, but my 6800XT is a red dragon(and an unusual one it has all its vrm's populated) that has a waterblock liquid metaled to it and an evc2se voltage controller, and I recently picked up a broken 3090 and repaired it, even with overclocking I can't get the 3090 as fast as the 6800XT, I think I'd have to shunt mod and waterblock it to.

Considering keeping the trash bucket 3090 for the huge vram and selling the 6800XT as it looks pristine and comes with air cooler and waterblock and I'm starting to run into games that are badly optimized that actually use all of the 16gb vram on the 6800XT, and the 3090 looks like it was thrown onto a highway then it went around town picking up STD's like it was catching pokemon so its resale value is poor

so if the 5000 series has some worthwhile overclocking well happy about that when I decide to upgrade

